2.2.2 GPIO API (pihwm_gpio.h)
-----------------------------

The following functions are defined for driving the GPIO interface.

 -- Function: int gpio_init (int PIN, char *DIR)
     Initialize the GPIO interface for the pin numbered PIN on the
     _Raspberry Pi_ P1 header in the direction specified by DIR.  DIR
     should be either `"in"' or `"out"', for which the defined
     constants `INPUT', `IN', `OUTPUT' or `OUT' may be used.

     Returns 1 on success and -1 on failure.

 -- Function: int gpio_release (int PIN)
     The inverse of `gpio_init'. Frees the  pin numbered PIN on the
     _Raspberry Pi_ P1 header, so it can be used for other purposes.

     Returns 1 on success and -1 on failure.

 -- Function: int gpio_write (int PIN, char *VAL)
     Set the pin numbered PIN on the _Raspberry Pi_ P1 header to the
     value specified by VAL.  DIR should be either `"0"' or `"1"'.  The
     defined constants `LOW' or `OFF' may be used instead of `0' and
     `HIGH' or `ON' instead of `1'/

     Returns 1 on success and -1 on failure.

 -- Function: int gpio_read (int PIN)
     Read the value on the pin numbered PIN on the _Raspberry Pi_ P1
     header.

     On success, returns 0 or 1 depending on whether the pin is low or
     high respectively. On failure returns -1.

 -- Function: int gpio_set_int (int PIN, void (*ISR) (int), char *MODE)
     Set INT as the interrupt service routine (ISR) for pin numbered
     PIN on the _Raspberry Pi_ P1 header.  MODE should be one of the
     strings `"rising"', `"falling"' or `"both"' to indicate which
     edge(s) the ISR is to be triggered on.

     The function ISR is called whenever the edge specified occurs,
     receiving as argument the number of the pin which triggered the
     interrupt.

     Returns 1 on success. Never fails!

 -- Function: int gpio_clear_int (int PIN)
     Clears any interrupt service routine (ISR) set on the pin numbered
     PIN on the _Raspberry Pi_ P1 header. The ISR will have been set
     originally by a call to `gpio_set_int'.

     Returns 0 on success. Never fails!

In addition to the standard functions, a number of convenience
functions are provided, which follow the Arduino style.

 -- Function: int pinMode (int PIN, char *VAL)
     This is a synonym for `gpio_init'/

 -- Function: int digitalWrite (int PIN, char *VAL)
     This is a near synonym for `gpio_write', except that `"HIGH"' is
     mapped to `"1' and `"LOW"' is mapped to `"0' before passing VAL.

 -- Function: int digitalRead (int PIN)
     This is a synonym for `gpio_read'.

 -- Function: int attachInterrupt (int PIN, void (*ISR) (int), char
          *MODE)
     This is a synonym for `gpio_set_interrupt'.

 -- Function: int detachInterrupt (int PIN)
     This is a synonym for `gpio_clear_int'.


