3.1.1 Setting up the SD card
----------------------------

The Occidentalis image can be found at

`http://learn.adafruit.com/adafruit-raspberry-pi-educational-linux-distro/occidentalis-v0-dot-2'.

Full details of how to put this on the SD card (it is not just a matter
of copying) for a range of operating systems (Windows, Linux, Mac) are
given at

`http://elinux.org/RPi_Easy_SD_Card_Setup'.

These is the short instructions for Linux. Run them from a shell.

  1. Unzip the image

  2. Use `df -h', then insert your SD card and rerun `df -h'. The new
     entries are the devices corresponding to your SD card. You'll
     probably see something like `/dev/mmcblk0p1' or `/dev/sdd1'. The
     `p1' or `1' are the partition number on the device, but we want to
     write the whole device, so we'll need to refer to it as
     `/dev/mmcblk0' or `/dev/sdd'

  3. We don't want anything else trying to write the SD card, so we now
     unmount it (leave it inserted). Use
          umount /dev/mmcblk0
     or
          umount /dev/sdd1

  4. Now use dd to copy the image to the device. Use the unzipped
     filename of the distribution and the device name _for the whole
     card_, not just the partition. For example:
          dd bs=4M if=Occidentalis_v02.img of=/dev/mmcblk0
     Change the filename and device name as appropriate.

     _Note._ This can take a long time (5-15 mins). You can check on
     progress by doing to another shell and running:
          sudo pkill -USR1 -n -x dd

  5. The image probably won't fill the entire SD card, particularly if
     it's large card. To fix this, use `gparted'. Run this and select
     the SD device (for example /dev/mmcblk0 or /dev/sdd). You'll see
     two partitions, one with a fat16 file system and one with an ext4
     file system. Select the ext4 partition and use
     Partition>Resize/Move to expand it to the maximum available size.
     Then use Edit>Apply Operations to change the size.


You now have an Occidentalis _Raspberry Pi_ image using all the space
available on your SD card.


