3.1.2 Setting up the Network
----------------------------

The _Raspberry Pi_ Occidentalis SD card is set up by default to accept
SSH. The Ethernet interface will use DHCP to request an appropriate IP
address. You can then connect to that address. For example if the IP
address allocated was 192.168.0.77, you could use:

     ssh pi@192.168.0.77

However for this to work, you need to know which DHCP address has been
allocated to your _Raspberry Pi_ card. If you are just using your home
router, you can easily look to see what the value is. But in a more
secure network environment this may not be possible.

Any router can be set up, so that a particular _Raspberry Pi_
(identified by its "MAC Address") will always be allocated the same IP
address. In a school environment it might be appropriate to set this up
for a classroom set of boards, labelling each board with the IP address.

In a standalone environment, it is good to be able to work without a
full routed network. This is particularly useful when using a laptop
with a standalone environment. To make this change, two modifications
are needed:

  1. On the _Raspberry Pi_ edit the `/etc/networks/interfaces' file.
     Comment out the lines referencing DHCP and setting up the WLAN
     (use the `#' character at the start of each line).

     Then add the following lines.
          iface eth0 inet static
          address 192.168.2.2
          network 255.255.255.0
          gateway 192.168.2.1

     This sets the _Raspberry Pi_ up to have an IP address of
     192.168.2.2 and connect to a host machine with IP address
     192.168.2.1 You can use other numbers, but it it good practice to
     start with 192.168, and the address and gateway must only differ
     in the last number.

  2. Then on the host machine (e.g. a laptop), edit the network
     connections for the fixed network. Almost certainly this is set to
     automatic. Change to manual and specify the network address as
     192.168.2.1. Don't specify a gateway.

     You should now be able to connect the _Raspberry Pi_ to the host
     machine by Ethernet and use `ssh' to log in

          ssh pi@192.168.2.2



